The Arab Monetary Fund yesterday announced that it had granted Egypt a new loan worth 87.7 million dinars (about $368 million). The loan agreement was signed by the Governor of the Central Bank of Egypt (CBE), Tarek Amer, and the AMF’s Chairman, Abdel Rahman Bin Abdullah Al-Hamidi. The AMF said in a statement that the loan’s goal was “to provide financial resources to support Egypt’s financial situation and meet the country’s urgent needs.” Over 12 Persons Killed As Gunmen Attack Repentant Bandits In… AU Suspends Burkina Faso After Military Coup Egypt recently received $639 million from the AMF. The new loan brings the total number of loans provided by the fund to Egypt to 15 agreements, with a total value of about $2.6 billion, according to the Enterprise. Egypt’s total external debt jumped to $137.85 billion in June, according to central bank data issued in October.